Zomato Data Analysis

About Dataset

Overview

Zomato has an average of 17.5 million monthly transacting customers for its food delivery business. Additionally, the average monthly active food delivery restaurant partners on Zomato's platform have also increased by 8.7% year-on-year, growing from 208,000 to 226,000.

This dataset provides insights into Zomato's food delivery operations, including restaurant types, customer preferences, votes, ratings, and approximate costs for two people. Through analyzing this data, we can uncover key trends in online ordering, customer behavior, and restaurant popularity.

EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS

1) What type of restaurant do the majority of customers order from?

In[12]:
type_counts = df['listed_in(type)'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
ax = sns.barplot(x=type_counts.index, y=type_counts.values)

plt.title('Majority of Customer Order ')
plt.xlabel('Restaurant Type')
plt.ylabel('Number of Orders')

for bars in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(bars)

plt.show()
INSIGHT :
  • The majority of customers prefer ordering from Dining restaurants, with a total of 110 orders.
  • Cafes follow as the second most popular type, with 23 orders.
  • Other types of restaurants have 8 orders.
  • Buffet restaurants are the least preferred with 7 orders.

2) How many votes has each type of restaurant received from customers?

In[13]:
votes_by_type = df.groupby('listed_in(type)')['votes'].sum()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
ax = sns.lineplot(x=votes_by_type.index, y=votes_by_type.values, marker='o', color='b')

plt.title('Number of Votes by Restaurant Type')
plt.xlabel('Restaurant Type')
plt.ylabel('Number of Votes')


for i, value in enumerate(votes_by_type.values):
    ax.text(i, value, str(value), ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()
INSIGHT
  • The majority of votes are received by Dining restaurants, with a total of 20,363 votes.
  • Other types of restaurants follow with 9,367 votes.
  • Cafes have 6,434 votes.
  • Buffet restaurants have the fewest votes, with 3,028 votes.

3) What are the ratings that the majority of restaurants have received?

In[14]:
ratings_count = df['rate'].value_counts().sort_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 4))
ax = sns.barplot(x=ratings_count.index, y=ratings_count.values, palette='Blues')

plt.title('Distribution of Ratings for Restaurants')
plt.xlabel('Rating (out of 5)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Restaurants')

for i, value in enumerate(ratings_count.values):
    ax.text(i, value, str(value), ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()
INSIGHT
  • The majority of restaurants have received a rating of 3.8, which is the most frequent rating with 20 occurrences. This indicates that the average customer satisfaction level is relatively high but not exceptional.
  • Additionally, ratings of 3.7 and 3.3 are also common, suggesting a general concentration of ratings in the mid to upper range of the scale.
  • Most restaurants are rated between 3.3 and 4.1, with 3.8 being the peak, reflecting a generally positive but varied level of customer satisfaction.

4) Zomato has observed that most couples order most of their food online. What is their average spending on each order?

In[15]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 4))
ax=sns.countplot(x=df['approx_cost(for two people)'])

for bars in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(bars)
INSIGHT
  • The majority of couples spend around 300 rupees on their food orders, with 23 occurrences at this price point.
  • The next most common spending amounts are 200 rupees and 150 rupees, each with 16 occurrences, followed by orders costing 400 rupees with 15 occurrences.
  • Most couples prefer affordable dining options, as the majority of the spending falls in the range of 200 to 500 rupees per order.
  • This suggests that Zomato can focus on promoting special offers for restaurants with meal options priced between 200 to 500 rupees to attract more couples who prefer ordering online.

5) Which mode (online or offline) has received the maximum rating?

In[24]:
max_rating_by_mode = df.groupby('online_order')['rate'].max()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
ax = sns.barplot(x=max_rating_by_mode.index, y=max_rating_by_mode.values, palette='viridis')

plt.title('Maximum Rating by Order Mode (Offline vs Online)')
plt.xlabel('Order Mode')
plt.ylabel('Maximum Rating')

for bars in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(bars, label_type='edge')

plt.show()


plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
colors = sns.color_palette('pastel')  
plt.pie(max_rating_by_mode.values, labels=max_rating_by_mode.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, colors=colors, wedgeprops={'edgecolor': 'black'})

plt.title('Maximum Rating by Order Mode ( Offline vs Online )', fontsize=14)

plt.show()
INSIGHT
  • Online orders have received the highest rating of 4.6 (51.7%), indicating a strong customer preference and satisfaction when ordering online.
  • Offline orders, while still well-rated, have received a slightly lower maximum rating of 4.3(48.3%).
  • This suggests that Zomato's online ordering system is meeting customer expectations more effectively, and future efforts could focus on further enhancing the offline experience to bridge the gap.

6) Which type of restaurant received more offline orders, so that Zomato can provide those customers with some good offers?

In[18]:
pivot_table = df.pivot_table(index='listed_in(type)', columns='online_order', aggfunc='size', fill_value=0)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
sns.heatmap(pivot_table, annot=True, cmap="YlGnBu", fmt='d')

plt.title("Heatmap of Orders by Restaurant Type and Order Mode")
plt.xlabel("Online Order")
plt.ylabel("Listed In (Type)")
plt.show()
INSIGHT
  • Dining restaurants received significantly more offline orders, with 77 offline orders compared to only 33 online orders.
  • This indicates that customers prefer placing orders in person at dining restaurants, making them a great target for offline offers and promotions.
  • Cafes, on the other hand, have a higher proportion of online orders, suggesting a different customer behavior for these types of establishments.

    ax.bar_label(bars, label_type='edge')

plt.title('Top 10 Restaurants Based on Votes')
plt.xlabel('Number of Votes')
plt.ylabel('Restaurant Name')
plt.show()

8) Top 10 Restaurants Based on Ratings

In[20]:
top_rated = df.sort_values(by='rate', ascending=False).head(10)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
colors = sns.color_palette('viridis', len(top_rated))  # Use the 'viridis' color palette

plt.pie(top_rated['rate'], labels=top_rated['name'], autopct=lambda p: '{:.1f}'.format(p * sum(top_rated['rate']) / 100), startangle=90, colors=colors, wedgeprops={'edgecolor': 'black'})

plt.title('Top 10 Restaurants Based on Ratings')
plt.show()

9) Top 10 Restaurants Based on Approximate Cost for Two People

In[21]:
top_costly = df.sort_values(by='approx_cost(for two people)', ascending=False).head(10)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
colors = sns.color_palette('viridis', len(top_costly))  # Use the 'viridis' color palette

plt.pie(top_costly['approx_cost(for two people)'], labels=top_costly['name'], autopct=lambda p: '{:.0f}'.format(p * sum(top_costly['approx_cost(for two people)']) / 100), startangle=90, colors=colors, wedgeprops={'edgecolor': 'black'})

plt.title('Top 10 Restaurants Based on Approximate Cost for Two People')
plt.show()

Project Learning

This project involved an in-depth analysis of Zomatos food delivery dataset, focusing on various aspects of restaurant performance and customer behavior. My aim was to derive meaningful insights that could inform Zomato's business strategies and enhance their platform's user experience. The dataset includes details such as restaurant types, customer ratings, online and offline ordering preferences, and approximate costs for two people. Heres a breakdown of our analysis:

  • Popular Restaurant Types: We analyzed which types of restaurantssuch as Dining, Cafes, Buffets, and Othersare most frequently chosen by customers. This analysis helps identify customer preferences and trends in dining habits.
  • Votes by Restaurant Type: We aggregated the total number of votes each restaurant type received to gauge its popularity and customer engagement. This insight is useful for understanding which restaurant categories are most favored by users.
  • Ratings Distribution: We examined the distribution of restaurant ratings to determine the most common ratings. This helps in assessing overall customer satisfaction and identifying trends in how customers rate their dining experiences.
  • Average Spending: We calculated the average expenditure for online orders. This information provides insights into how much customers typically spend on their orders, which can inform pricing strategies and promotions.
  • Comparison of Ratings by Order Mode: We compared the ratings received by online and offline orders to understand how each mode affects customer satisfaction. This comparison highlights whether online or offline ordering leads to better-rated experiences.
  • Offline Orders Analysis: We identified which types of restaurants receive more offline orders. This analysis helps in targeting promotional offers and improving marketing strategies for restaurant types that are more popular for in-person dining.

By leveraging these insights, Zomato can tailor its marketing strategies, enhance customer experience, and optimize its partnerships with restaurants. By understanding customer preferences, spending habits, and satisfaction levels, Zomato can enhance its service offerings and drive growth on its platform. This analysis contributes to a deeper understanding of consumer behavior and helps in making data-driven decisions for improving service quality and customer satisfaction. This project underscores the importance of data-driven decision-making in the food delivery industry.
